<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Nurturing Students' Healthy Lifestyles a Priority for UCF</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Sam Gardner
		
		<span class="date">Nov. 16, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE511/en_US/cardiocrop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: UCF News File</p>
			
			<p>The UCF Recreation and Wellness Center offers cardio equipment, a floor full of weights, a lap pool, a leisure pool and many athletic courts.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004105bd60439010c0c76ce2f00454d">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:khallida@mail.ucf.edu">Kim Halliday, Recreation and Wellness Center</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-2408</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:pwilkhu@mail.ucf.edu">Preeti Wilkhu</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0366</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.rec.ucf.edu">Recreation and Wellness Center</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.shs.ucf.edu/wellness">Reach for Wellness</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.imsports.ucf.edu/">Intramural sports at UCF</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Counting calories and pumping iron are just the beginning for UCF students who want to maintain healthy lifestyles. Many health and fitness organizations on campus provide a variety of other services to help students stay in top shape. </p><p>The Recreation and <place /><placename />Wellness</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place /> offers courses in ballet, yoga, flexibility training and group exercise, along with a climbing wall and a year-round intramural sports program. </p><p>Students can receive free health and lifestyle assessments at Reach for Wellness, located on the first floor of the Recreation and <place /><placename />Wellness</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place />. And students can meet with registered dietitians or attend workshops to learn more about eating healthier and sports nutrition.</p><p>An average student needs at least 30 minutes of physical activity per day, said UCF fitness specialist Kim Halliday. The exercise can come from walking, working out or other activities.</p><p>Working out is something you have to make time for, Halliday said. You have to have goals and make time for yourself. You have to keep yourself interested and change up your routine every once in a while.</p><p>The Recreation and <place /><placename />Wellness</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place /> offers cardio equipment, a floor full of weights, a lap pool, a leisure pool and many athletic courts. A challenge course and a climbing tower round out the resources available at no cost for UCF students. Personal training is offered at a cost of $20 per hourlong session.</p><p>UCF also promotes a year-round intramural sports program. Athletes can register as teams or individuals at a variety of levels, from recreational to competitive. The leagues vary from the traditional football, baseball and basketball to the more innovative dodge ball, Wiffle ball, badminton and inner tube water polo.</p><p>UCF also is home to more than 30 sports clubs. Mens and womens lacrosse, rugby, soccer and water polo are offered, as well as crew, table tennis, bowling and martial arts.</p><p>Reach for Wellness is a peer-education service that promotes low-risk, responsible decision making through workshops and promotions. Workshops cover topics such as safe sex and birth control options, as well as body image and eating disorders.<span>  </span></p><p><span></span>Reach for Wellness also provides confidential HIV tests at a cost of $15 and offers relaxation therapy and lifestyle consultations. Peer educators give presentations in classrooms and residence halls about nutrition, exercise and other health and wellness issues.</p><p>We look to teach students to make good choices when it comes to high-risk behavior, Kelly Ferris, a peer educator for Reach for Wellness.</p><p>UCFs registered and licensed dietitians can discuss weight management and eating disorders, along with sports nutrition, food supplements and many other topics. Recent presentations, which suggest a number of options for evaluating and improving food choices, include Eating for Better Energy and Weight Woes.<span>  </span></p><p><span></span>An average college diet includes many high-carbohydrate and high-fat foods that, when mixed with low water intake and a lack of fruits and vegetables, can prove to be harmful. UCF dietitian Preeti Wilkhu said she believes convenience is the primary influence behind a damaging routine, but she also said it is easy to make the proper adjustments to maintain a healthy diet.</p><p>You can buy Ramen noodles, but you can also buy canned chicken or canned tuna and make a healthy sandwich instead, Wilkhu said.</p><p>Fast food is a common staple among college students, and Wilkhu contends that totally eliminating fast food is not a necessity to healthy eating habits.</p><p>If you do your homework, youll find that not all fast food is unhealthy, Wilkhu said. Any fast food can be healthy depending on what you choose and how much you choose to eat.</p><p>Wilkhu added that high blood pressure, high cholesterol and diabetes dont know if youre healthy, or unhealthy, skinny or fat, white or black, or male or female. Just because you are skinny, it doesnt give you the right to eat all the junk food you want.</p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

